show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>10918</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00BN</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00BN.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Event structure</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>26</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="source"><fr:link
href="staton-winskel-2010.xml"
type="local"
addr="staton-winskel-2010">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>An <fr:em>event structure</fr:em> is defined to be triple <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( E, \mathsf { Con } _{ E } ,  \leq _E \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> where <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> is a partial order of <fr:em>events</fr:em> partially ordered by the <fr:em>causal dependency relation</fr:em> <fr:tex>\leq _E</fr:tex>, and <fr:tex>\mathsf { Con } _{ E } \subseteq   \mathcal {P} _{ \mathit {fin} } { \mathopen {} \left ( E \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> specifies when a finite subset of <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> is <fr:em>consistent</fr:em>, satisfying the following laws:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>every downset of <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> is finite;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>every singleton set is consistent;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>any subset of a consistent subset is consistent;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>for any consistent subset <fr:tex>x \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>e \leq  e'</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>e' \in  x</fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex>x \cup { \mathopen {} \left \{ e \right \} \mathclose {}} \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>The definition of <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structure</fr:link> only speaks of <fr:em>finite</fr:em> consistent subsets; these are extended to arbitrary subsets as follows.</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>10920</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00BP</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00BP.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Consistent subsets of an <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structure</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>26</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A subset <fr:tex>x \subseteq  E</fr:tex> of an <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structure</fr:link> is said to be <fr:em>consistent</fr:em> when any finite subset of <fr:tex>x</fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex>\mathsf { Con } _{ E }</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>10922</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00BO</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00BO.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Configurations of an <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structure</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>26</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="source"><fr:link
href="staton-winskel-2010.xml"
type="local"
addr="staton-winskel-2010">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em>configuration</fr:em> of an <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structure</fr:link> <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> is defined to be a <fr:link
href="jms-00BP.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BP">consistent</fr:link>, downward-closed subset of <fr:tex>E</fr:tex>. We will write <fr:tex>\mathcal {C} _{ E }</fr:tex> for the set of all configurations of <fr:tex>E</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\mathcal {C} _{ E }^{ \mathit {fin} }</fr:tex> for the set of <fr:em>finite</fr:em> configurations of <fr:tex>E</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>10924</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00BR</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00BR.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Rigid morphisms of <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structures</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>10</fr:month><fr:day>26</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:meta
name="source"><fr:link
href="staton-winskel-2010.xml"
type="local"
addr="staton-winskel-2010">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em>rigid morphism</fr:em> of <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structures</fr:link> <fr:tex>{ E } \xrightarrow {{ f }}{ E' }</fr:tex> is a monotone function on events that preserves finite <fr:link
href="jms-00BO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BO">configurations</fr:link> and is <fr:em>locally injective</fr:em> in the sense that for any finite <fr:link
href="jms-00BO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BO">configuration</fr:link> <fr:tex>x \in \mathcal {C} _{ E }^{ \mathit {fin} }</fr:tex> and events <fr:tex>e_1,e_2 \in  x</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>fe_1 = fe_2</fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex>e_1=e_2</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>I have not checked whether the appropriate <fr:link
href="jms-004K.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004K">structure identity principle</fr:link> holds for the (pre)category of <fr:link
href="jms-00BN.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BN">event structures</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="jms-00BR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00BR">rigid morphisms</fr:link>. If it does not hold, this would suggest that a new <fr:em>univalent</fr:em> definition of event structure is needed.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
